## Findings

The codebase is a small Express + TypeScript API. Here's what I found:

### Current State
- **`src/routes.ts`** — the `GET /users` handler simply does `res.json(users)`, returning all 15 users as a flat array
- **`src/data.ts`** — 15 hardcoded in-memory users
- **`tests/routes.test.ts`** — tests are **already written** for the paginated API and are currently failing

### Plan: One file, one change

Only **`src/routes.ts`** needs to be modified. Replace the current handler with:

```typescript
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page  = parseInt(req.query.page  as string, 10) || 1;
  const limit = parseInt(req.query.limit as string, 10) || 10;

  const total      = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const startIndex = (page - 1) * limit;

  const data = users.slice(startIndex, startIndex + limit);

  res.json({
    data,
    pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages },
  });
});
```

**Why this satisfies all 4 test cases:**
| Test | Behaviour |
|---|---|
| Default (no params) | `page=1, limit=10` → 10 users, `totalPages=2` |
| `?page=2&limit=10` | `startIndex=10` → users 11–15 (5 items) |
| `?limit=5` | `totalPages = ceil(15/5) = 3` |
| `?page=100` | `slice(990, 1000)` returns `[]` naturally — 200, not an error |

The two existing `GET /users/:id` tests are untouched and will continue to pass.
